<br>
Of course, that needs to be achieved without making the light tank into an even better tank, so you can't jack up evade/parry or add evade/parry styles until people decide it's better to attack the heavy tank than the light tank.  Not to mention that if most of our damage comes from evade/parry styles, then we won't be filling our role (assist tank) properly.<br>
<br>
So what about a defensive skill that raises our defense drastically, but reduces our offense similarly?<br>
<br>
To exaggerate: Skill X - while skill is up, makes every melee attack on the blademaster automatically miss, but also makes every attack BY the blademaster also miss.<br>
<br>
So in RvR... Blademaster and Hero gang up on, say, a paladin.  Paladin notices Blademaster is hurting him much more (of course this needs to be true, heh), so paladin turns to Blademaster.  Blademaster turns on Skill X.  Now Blademaster and Paladin aren't hurting anybody, but Hero is hurting Paladin.  Paladin notices this is no good, so turns back to Hero.  Blademaster now turns off Skill X, and combat continues as before.<br>
<br>
Blademaster is NOT a better PvE tank now, though, since he is unable to hurt mobs and therefore get aggro.<br>
<br>
Of course, having every attack miss is probably a bit extreme, but the concept is, I think, valid, and with proper testing, I'm sure someone can come up with numbers that balance this all out.<br>
<br>
It probably shouldn't be a skill with a set duration, since it'd be too easy for enemies to turn on the blademaster, wait till he turns on the skill, then turn back, effectively having nullified the blademaster for the duration of the skill.<br>
<br>
The skill could even be automatic, adjusting the blademaster's damage output (or to-hit rate, rather) and defense depending on whether he's being attacked or not.<br>
<br>
It could be a trainable skill (ugh, not good), being more &quot;extreme&quot; (more misses on both sides) the higher it is; or maybe a &quot;free&quot; skill like Evade, with several levels, each one better than the one before.<br>
<br>
I see two problems, though... soloing (if the skill is automatic, you can't solo...), and the potential to abuse the skill to be immune to mobs (auto or on/off... run into a dungeon, turn on the skill if needed, run wherever... as long as mobs don't cast on you, you won't get hurt).<br>
<br>
Both those problems can be fixed by making it an RvR-only skill, but that seems kinda contrived.  Maybe it can be made to work only against targets that are engaged by someone else... ?<br>
<br>
Lemme know what you think..<br>
